<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  most don’t have the sense to lock them away in their safe. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A locked away gun is of little use for your protection if that is the reason you purchased it. I carry mine. On the only occasion I have had to actually pull it in the 5 years I have carried, the mere sight of the weapon stopped the assailant. There is easier prey out there than an armed man defending his family. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  the simple fact that hundreds of weapons we just so casually strewn about on display tables made me cringe in fear. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I am sure they were all illegally obtained and being bought by criminals that day as well. I don't know about texas, but when I went to a show here, you had to display a permit to purchase the gun on the spot. Others had to wait.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Anybody catch that 60 minutes episode about a year ago where an undercover reporter bought a semi-automatic with NO identification, then proceded to buy a fully automatic modification kit for said weapon a few minutes later? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Leave it to the media. That one instance is the precidence too correct? Guess what, You can buy a MAC 10 and a file and have an automatic weapon in minutes. Still, how many MAC 10s do you read about being used in crimes?<br>
<br>
Let's do a quick sumation on my view:<br>
<br>
Trying to outlaw handguns would be idiotic. There are too many out there and the folks you would be taking them from are the one's abiding by the law. Do you honestly believe if you outlawed guns, they would all disappear? I don't. Check out the problems Austrailia had when they tried.<br>
<br>
Handguns may be too easy to obtain in some areas. The movie view of going to the corner and passing a guy a few hundred for an assault rifle is bullshit though.<br>
<br>
An armed victim is a harder target than an unarmed victim. An assailant is going to pass over the person he thinks will fight back if easier prey is available.<br>
<br>
Owning a firearm requires you to assume certain responsibilities. You should know how to use and care for it. It is your responsibility to keep it out of the hands of children or other that should not have it. You have to accept that it is you last means of defence. Someone is willing to take you wallet and leave you and your family unharmed? Let em. Someone intends you harm? Fight back. I will admit that tons of situations make it a hard call, but if you have to kill a person, you have to live with that guilt. If there was a way to avoid it and you didn't, you shouldn't be carrying one.<br>
<br>
Statistics can be used to support both sides. It's amazing how well folks can twist em. Not just for this. The media is the worst. Anyone else notice when the founder of Mother Against Drunk Driving got a DUI, it was a snippet in the corner of the paper? It wasn't politically correct to hang her out to dry, so the media backed off.<br>
<br>
I don't support the NRA's view that citizens should be allowed to posses assault wepons. The problem you have there is the definition. My carry gun of choice is a H&amp;K USP Compact in a .40 S&amp;W. That same gun was issued to seal teams at one point so technically it could be defined an assault weapon. I tend to think of assault wepons in terms of fully automatic weapons.<br>
<br>
Half measures don't work. A few years back, a law was passed so you could only get 10 round clips unless you were in law enforcement. I have PERSONALLY seen someone that was dead, in their car, shot 10 times. I doubt they would be anymore dead if they had been shot 15 times. Teflon &quot;cop killer&quot; bullets are illegal, yet they can still be obtained if you want.<br>
<br>
Is there a simple solution? No. It's as messy as discussing religion or politics. You have both extremes and alot of folks in the middle ground (where I place myself).<br>
<br>
I believe in my right to bear arms.<br>
<br>
I believe in my right to protect myself and my family against someone that would interfere with my right of &quot;life, liberty, and pursuit of happiness(that includes being alive)&quot;. It would pain me to my dieing day to take someone else's life intentionally but I would to protect myself and my family. It's a trade off.<br>
<br>
I believe that firearm owners should be responsible. Thre is nothing worse than a loaded gun in the hands of someone that has no respect for the weapon.<br>
<br>
I FIRMLY believe the folks on both extremes (Outlaw em all! vs Every citizen should own a 30 cal machine gun!) are idiots.<br>
<br>
Anyways, sorry for the long ramble but it's a topic that gets my ire up. Guns dont kill people. People kill people.<br>
<br>
Blearchie Pooh<br>
Phantasmist of CoFE<br>
